JOHANNESBURG - The ancient Baobab tree is under threat according to a new study by the scientific journal, Nature Plants. Scientists say that in the last few years, a number of the iconic trees have died in the Southern African region.
	
	Nine of the trees that died were aged between 1,000 and 2,500-years. IN PICS: 4 Heritage sites in SA parks Scientists say it's practically impossible for such a high number of the trees to die from natural causes within such a short space of time. They believe rising temperatures and increasing drought conditions are among factors driving this. All the deaths occurred in Botswana, Namibia, South Africa, Zambia, and Zimbabwe. eNCA